{
  "doc_id": "52837",
  "text": "For Western populations, for instance, Rolland-Cachera et al. found that children who experienced AR earlier had a higher adiposity at age 16 years compared to those who experienced a later AR [CITATION_1] . Prokopec and Bellisle showed that there was an inverse relationship between age at AR and BMI in adulthood while BMI itself varied during growth in an European population [CITATION_2] . Accordingly, AR may be a useful indicator associated with lifestyle diseases through high adult BMI [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . A recent review by Brisbois et al. concluded that AR, maternal BMI, and father's employment were associated with adult obesity [CITATION_6] . Among these factors, only AR is a practical candidate indicator that can be used for intervention in children to prevent adult obesity. Children who experience AR earlier may represent a high-risk group, and measures to prevent obesity may be implemented for these individuals.",
